eanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Arches","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  Norman, English: locative name from any of various places in France called Arques (Eure, Pas-de-Calais, Seine-Maritime). The name was sometimes reduced to   Arch  .","2  English: variant of   Arch   with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Arch","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone living by a bridge, from Middle English, Old French <i>arche</i> ‘arch’ (i.e. of a bridge).","English (of Norman origin): shortened form of <b>Arches</b>, a habitational name from any of various places in France called Arques (Eure, Pas-de-Calais, Seine-Maritime).","Germanized form of Slovenian <b>Arh</b>: from a shortened form of the personal name <i>Areh</i>, an old vernacular form of <i>Henrik</i> (see   Henry   1)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Robert de Arches was born about 1202, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with Robert de Arches."},"et":{"about 1202–":"umbes 1202–Surnud","1198–Male":"1198–Surnud","1228–Female":"1228–Surnud","1202–Female":"1202–Surnud","1228":"1228","about 1228":"umbes 1228","1202":"1202","about 1202":"umbes 1202","1198":"1198","Wrawby, Lincolnshire, England":"Wrawby, Lincolnshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1202–":"noin 1202–Kuollut","1198–Male":"1198–Kuollut","1228–Female":"1228–Kuollut","1202–Female":"1202–Kuollut","1228":"1228","about 1228":"noin 1228","1202":"1202","about 1202":"noin 1202","1198":"1198","Wrawby, Lincolnshire, England":"Wrawby, Lincolnshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1202–":"environ 1202–Décédée","1198–Male":"1198–Décédé","1228–Female":"1228–Décédée","1202–Female":"1202–Décédée","1228":"1228","about 1228":"environ 1228","1202":"1202","about 1202":"environ 1202","1198":"1198","Wrawby, Lincolnshire, England":"Wrawby, Lincolnshire, Angleterre","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Robert de Arches est née environ 1202, à Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Robert de Arches."},"de":{"about 1202–":"um 1